statement.p:
Write each power as a radical. 

x^{2/3}

t^{-3/2}

w^{1.25}

z^{-0.4}

solution.p:
Recall that the numerator of the exponent is the power and the denominator is the root.  A negative exponent indicates a reciprocal.

x^{2/3} = \sqrt[3]{x^2}

t^{-3/2} = \dfrac{1}{t^{3/2}} = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{t^3}}

w^{1.25} = w^{5/4} = \sqrt[4]{w^5}

z^{-0.4} = \dfrac{1}{z^{4/10}} = \dfrac{1}{z^{2/5}} = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt[5]{z^2}}

statement.p:
 Write each radical expression in exponential form and simplify.

\sqrt[4]{b^3}

\dfrac{1}{\sqrt[6]{a^3}}

x^2\sqrt[4]{x}

\dfrac{\sqrt[3]{v}}{\sqrt{v}}

Write each power as a radical. 

m^{-3/5}

p^{2.75}

x^{0.18}

 Write each radical expression in exponential form and simplify.

\sqrt[10]{n^9}

\sqrt{h}\sqrt[4]{h}

\left(\sqrt[3]{t^2}\right)^4

 Find the value of the exponent.

3^x=81

5^x=\dfrac{1}{125}

\left(\dfrac{3}{4}\right)^x=\dfrac{16}{9}

64^x=16

li.p:
We can write both sides with base 4.
        64 = 4^3~~~ \text{and}~~~16 = 4^2, 
        so 
         ~(4^3)^x \amp = 4^2 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Multiply exponents.}}
            4^{3x} \amp = 4^2  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Equate exponents.}}
            3x \amp = 2
            x \amp =\dfrac{2}{3}

statement.p:
Find the value of the exponent.

2^x = \dfrac{1}{1024}

125^x = 25

solution.p:
When multiplying two powers with the same base, we add the exponents. Notice that the base does not change.

1.35^6(1.35^4) = 1.35^{6+4}=1.35^{10}

0.64^5(0.64^n) = 0.64^{5+n}

statement.p:
Use the laws of exponents to simplify.

\dfrac{0.32^8}{0.32^2}

\dfrac{0.32^t}{0.32^x}

solution.p:
 When dividing two powers with the same base, we subtract the exponents.

\dfrac{0.32^8}{0.32^2} = 0.32^{8-2} = 0.32^6

\dfrac{0.32^t}{0.32^x} = 0.32^{t-x}

 When raising a power to a power, we multiply the exponents.

\left(1.07^5\right)^3 = 1.07^{15}

\left(1.07^4\right)^p = 1.07^{4p}
